==English==

===Etymology===
From {{S.}} ''[[embargar]]'' 'to arrest' and {{E.}} ''[[barge]]'' 'to force'.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP|US}} {{IPA|/əmˈbɑrdʒ/}}
*Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɑː(r)dʒ|-ɑː(r)dʒ]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|embarg|es}}

# {{rfv-sense}} {{transitive}} To impose oneself upon another, often against their will.
# {{rfv-sense}} {{transitive}} To forcefully share an unwanted opinion.
#*In his love for her, he had unintentionally '''embarged''' himself upon her, and only wanted her to return the love he so dearly felt for her.
# {{transitive}} To [[embargo]].
# {{intransitive}} To board a [[barge]].
# {{intransitive}} To [[embark]].

